# Project instructions — Spec-Driven Development

> This is a **generic, sanitized example**. Copy it into your own project as `CLAUDE.md` (or merge it into an existing one) and adjust the stack-specific details — nothing here should be treated as universal just because it's the default.

## Development mode

This project uses Spec-Driven Development (SDD).

For non-trivial changes, follow this workflow:

1. Create or update a `SPEC.md`.
2. Clarify and strengthen the spec before planning.
3. Create or update a `PLAN.md`.
4. Analyze consistency before implementing.
5. Implement only the tasks described in the spec.
6. Do not introduce behavior that is not covered by the spec.
7. If something is ambiguous, document the assumption or decision in `DECISIONS.md`.

## Project constitution

If the project has a `specs/CONSTITUTION.md`, read it before planning or implementing non-trivial changes. Project rules in this file must be respected unless explicitly overridden by the user.

If it does not exist, run `/project-init` to create it before starting any spec.

## SDD structure

Feature specifications live under:

`specs/features/`

Expected structure:

```
specs/features/001-feature-name/
├── SPEC.md
├── PLAN.md
├── TASKS.md
└── DECISIONS.md
```

## File purpose

- `SPEC.md` — defines what and why.
- `PLAN.md` — defines the implementation strategy.
- `TASKS.md` — defines small, actionable tasks.
- `DECISIONS.md` — records assumptions and technical decisions.
- `specs/CONSTITUTION.md` — permanent engineering rules for the project.

## Spec status lifecycle

```
Draft → Ready → In Progress → In Review → Done | Archived
```

- `Draft` — spec created, not yet plannable.
- `Ready` — plan and tasks exist, implementation can start.
- `In Progress` — at least one task has been implemented.
- `In Review` — all tasks complete and spec-review passed — QA and specialized reviews pending.
- `Done` — all reviews complete and spec-close run — ready for PR.
- `Archived` — spec abandoned or superseded.

## Workflow selection

Use `/sdd` as the main entry point for any non-trivial feature — it auto-detects complexity and selects the medium or full workflow.

If the change touches authentication, authorization, user data, tenant isolation, public APIs, file uploads, secrets, database schema, migrations, or persistence, `/sdd` selects the full workflow automatically.

Use `/sdd-medium` or `/sdd-full` only when you want to force a specific workflow explicitly.

Use `/spec-status <feature-folder>` when a feature already exists and the next step is unclear.

## Global SDD guardrails

Before planning, implementing, or closing a feature, apply the consistency guardrails:

`skills/sdd-guardrails/SKILL.md`

Do not implement if:

- active decisions contradict each other
- a plan is obsolete, partial, superseded, or marked needs-review
- acceptance criteria and tasks are not aligned
- the source of truth differs between SPEC/PLAN/TASKS/DECISIONS
- money/unit/deployment rules are unclear
- a scope change invalidated the current plan

> If you maintain a shared skill set across multiple projects instead of copying `skills/` into each repo, point this at wherever that shared location lives on your machine, e.g. `<central-claude-config>/skills/sdd-guardrails/SKILL.md` — just don't hardcode a path that only exists on one machine into a repo other people will clone.

## Available skills

- `/project-init` — initialize a project's SDD structure: creates `specs/CONSTITUTION.md` by interviewing the user about stack, architecture rules, coding conventions, and review gates. Run once per project before creating any specs.
- `/sdd` — main entry point: auto-detects complexity and guides the right workflow.
- `/sdd-medium`, `/sdd-full` — force a specific workflow explicitly.
- `/sdd-orchestrate` — run the SDD workflow with multi-model delegation (deep-reasoner on Opus, fast-worker on Sonnet) — see "Multi-model orchestration" below.
- `/prototype` — explore whether an approach is viable before writing a spec.
- `/decision-mapping` — turn a vague idea into a sequenced map of investigation tickets when too many questions remain to write a spec.
- `/spec-create` — create a new feature specification (includes an auto-clarify pass).
- `/spec-clarify` — deepen spec clarification when blocking questions remain.
- `/spec-status` — overview of all specs, or a deep-dive/resume of a single feature.
- `/spec-close` — close a completed feature: resolve open questions, generate an implementation summary.
- `/spec-plan` — convert a specification into an implementation plan and task list.
- `/spec-analyze` — analyze consistency between spec, plan, tasks, and decisions before implementation.
- `/spec-implement` — implement the next pending task from a feature spec.
- `/spec-update` — update an existing spec mid-implementation, propagating changes to plan and tasks.
- `/spec-review` — review implementation against the spec, plan, and tasks.
- `/spec-resume` — resume an in-progress feature without re-reading the full spec.
- `/qa-review` — review functional quality, edge cases, regressions, and tests.
- `/security-review` — review authentication, authorization, data exposure, file upload, secrets, and API risks.
- `/database-review` — review schema changes, migrations, indexes, queries, transactions, data integrity, and rollback risks.
- `/performance-review` — review N+1 queries, re-renders, caching, bundle size, algorithmic complexity, and performance risks.
- `/api-review` — review API contracts, backward compatibility, versioning, DTOs, and error semantics.
- `/backend-review` — backend-focused review of APIs, services, data access, and business logic.
- `/frontend-review` — frontend-focused review of components, rendering, state, and UX correctness.
- `/seo-review` — review public-facing pages for metadata, Open Graph, JSON-LD, Core Web Vitals, sitemap, and canonical URLs.
- `/privacy-compliance-review` — review data-protection compliance risks (adapt the specific regulation to your jurisdiction).
- `/refactor-review` — optional cleanup review before spec-close.
- `/review-all` — run all applicable specialized reviews in one command.
- `/pr-description` — generate a pull request description from the current diff and related specs.
- `/architect-review` — analyze architecture, diagnose root causes, and evaluate trade-offs.
- `/test-engineer` — design test strategy, identify coverage gaps, enforce TDD.
- `/debugger` — trace bugs and build failures to their root cause.
- `/handoff` — compact the current conversation into a document for a fresh session to continue.

## Recommended workflow (adapt per feature type)

For most features:

1. `/spec-create` (includes auto-clarify)
2. `/spec-plan`
3. `/spec-analyze`
4. `/spec-implement`
5. `/spec-review`
6. `/qa-review`
7. Specialized reviews as detected by `/spec-analyze` (database, security, performance, API, backend, frontend, SEO, privacy)
8. `/spec-close`
9. `/pr-description`

## Rules

- Do not start implementation before a plan exists.
- Keep changes small and reviewable.
- Prefer existing project patterns over new abstractions.
- Add or update tests when behavior changes.
- Do not change unrelated files.
- Do not implement behavior that is not described in the active spec.
- Do not silently make architectural decisions; document them in `DECISIONS.md`.
- Every task in `TASKS.md` should map back to one or more acceptance criteria.
- Mark tasks as completed only when the implementation is actually done.
- If tests cannot be run, explain why.

## Review rules

Before considering a feature complete, run the reviews relevant to what the change touches — see `/spec-analyze`'s detection rules for which ones apply. Don't run every specialized review on every change; run the ones the spec actually triggers.

## Scope control

For small, trivial changes, SDD is optional. Examples: typo fixes, small styling tweaks, renaming a local variable, minor copy changes, isolated one-line bug fixes.

For non-trivial changes, SDD is required. Examples: new features, backend changes, frontend flows, API changes, database changes, security-sensitive changes, multi-file refactors, changes involving business logic or external integrations.

## Small-change shortcut

For small, low-risk changes, skip SDD documents and use a direct instruction instead:

"Make this small change. Do not create specs. Do not modify unrelated files. Summarize only files changed and tests run."

## Token economy

- Keep responses concise and actionable.
- Do not repeat full contents of specs, plans, tasks, decisions, or constitution files.
- Read only the active feature folder unless explicitly asked.
- Avoid scanning unrelated files or archived specs unless explicitly asked.
- Prefer summaries over pasted file contents.
- Suggest the next command instead of re-explaining the full workflow.
- **Graph-first:** if `.graphify/GRAPH_REPORT.md` exists (legacy fallback: root
  `GRAPH_REPORT.md`), derive impact and reading lists from it — preferring
  `graphify review-context <file>` / `graphify affected-flows <file>` when the
  CLI is available — before any repo-wide Glob/Grep/Read sweep. The graph bounds
  what to read; the code remains the source of truth.

<!-- SDD-ORCHESTRATION:START -->
## Multi-model orchestration

This project can run the SDD workflow with multi-model delegation (see
`docs/SDD-ORCHESTRATION.md` in the SDD repo). Entry point: `/sdd-orchestrate <goal>`.

Roles:

- **Orchestrator (main session — Fable when available, otherwise Sonnet):** classify the
  task, keep the main context clean, create/update SPEC/PLAN/TASKS/DECISIONS, decide and
  review every delegation, run QA against acceptance criteria. Avoid doing extensive
  mechanical work directly.
- **`deep-reasoner` (Opus, read-only):** architecture, complex debugging, root cause,
  security, concurrency, idempotency, race conditions, data consistency, delicate
  migrations, distributed systems, risk analysis, SPEC/PLAN review, high-risk
  implementation review. It analyzes and recommends; it never edits.
- **`fast-worker` (Sonnet):** implement approved, well-delimited tasks; create/update
  tests; mechanical refactors; boilerplate; docs; run verifications. It stops and returns
  the task when it hits an undocumented architectural decision.

Delegation rules:

- Never use Opus for copy, formatting, boilerplate, or trivial changes.
- Never delegate vague tasks ("implement the whole feature") — split into small tasks
  with stable IDs, allowed files, done-criteria, and mandatory tests.
- Never run in parallel two delegations that could modify the same files, the same
  contract, the same migration, the same domain state, or high-conflict shared tests.
- Delegate by objective with a bounded brief; never dump the whole conversation. Request
  summarized, structured answers. Reuse findings; avoid redundant investigations.
- Analysis/audit/investigation/review/design requests produce a report — no
  implementation unless explicitly requested.
- Fallbacks (never block on a missing model): no Fable → orchestrate on Sonnet; no Opus →
  Sonnet analyst in a separate context + note in DECISIONS.md; no Sonnet → nearest
  available model. Never invent model identifiers.
<!-- SDD-ORCHESTRATION:END -->

## Project-specific extensions

This is the place for rules specific to *your* stack, tooling, or machine setup — for example, preview-server conventions for a particular framework, a required local dev-server restart procedure, or team-specific lint rules. Keep those out of the generic sections above so this file stays reusable across projects; add them here explicitly scoped to when they apply.
